<TEXT>
paris is the venue for many strategy sessions 
dedicated to the defense and promotion of the french language but 
this one had a distinctively american accent 
there was virgil benoit of red lake falls minn who noted that 
the motto on his state flag was letoile du nord the northern 
star 
there was randolph lineham a lawyer from long beach calif 
whose ancestors emigrated in 1870 when prussia annexed the alsace 
region and there was floyd satterlee of indianapolis with no 
french connection other than a love of the language and culture 
they were among 45 delegates from 20 states representing the 
estimated 15 million frenchspeaking us citizens who gathered 
in paris last week to assess the prospects for the language of 
voltaire in the land of french toast and french fries 
the bestknown frenchspeakers in the united states are likely 
louisianas nearly 600000 cajuns but there are frenchspeaking 
communities from maine to the pacific conference delegates said 
lineham said speaking french has been considered chic in certain 
california circles for a long time the francophone community there 
continues to grow with the arrival of immigrants from the former 
french colonies of cambodia and vietnam 
more than half the delegates in paris were professors 
normand beaupre a university teacher and writer from biddeford 
maine still remembers when francoamericans were called the 
chinese of the east because many of them worked in new england 
textile mills 
we were told speak american he said 
beaupre 55 says its no longer a liability to be a 
frenchspeaking american 
i have my own identity he said i am not a quebecer nor 
a frenchman nor a cajun i am a francoamerican 
the 1980 census registered 13 million americans of french 
origin the first french arrived at the end of the 16th century 
and france lost its last territory in the presentday us with the 
louisiana purchase in 1803 
the threeday meeting was organized by a french association 
formed 13 years ago to strengthen ties with frenchspeaking 
americans the french foreign ministry and paris mayors office 
provided part of the funding 
at the close of the conference delegates voted to seek improved 
teaching of french at us schools promote frenchoriented local 
festivals and push for a greater availability of tv programs and 
written material in french 
after the second generation the french language is very often 
lost by the children beaupre said we need a new strategy and 
this is to link with the international francophone movement rather 
than staying alone in each state 
</TEXT>
