<TEXT>
it involves just one newspaper and fewer than 
2500 workers but to organized labor which has stumbled from one 
debacle to another in the last decade the daily news strike has 
the feel of a last stand 
these days every strike like this one seems to be about the 
survival of the union movement said james green professor of 
labor studies at the university of massachusettsboston union 
people ask themselves if we lose another one why are unorganized 
workers going to join a union 
and they ask themselves if we cant win in new york where can 
we win 
new york city is so damn important to the american union 
movement said aflcio spokesman rex hardesty in washington 
like they say everything else is hoboken 
with about 40 percent of its work force organized new york is 
one of the few big cities that can still pass for a union town 
the news strike began oct 25 after a paper handler who was 
working while seated refused a supervisors order to stand up 
saying he needed to sit down because of a physical disability when 
other workers walked out in sympathy the company hired permanent 
replacements within 24 hours nine unions were on strike 
since then management has been more successful at producing a 
newspaper than distributing it most newsstand dealers refuse to 
sell the news usually because of striker appeals threats or 
outright violence 
circulation has dropped from a millionplus to about 500000 
and many leading advertisers have pulled out including department 
stores such as macys and alexanders 
the news battle comes at a crucial period in us labor history 
union members a majority of the work force 40 years ago now 
account for less than 20 percent the last decade was marked by a 
series of embarrassing defeats or costly standoffs 
against this background the news dispute is variously described 
as labors alamo or its waterloo 
certain strikes rise to national attention and become symbolic 
strikes says ronald filippelli editor of an encyclopedia on 
labor strife they become much more important than the number of 
people involved 
local strike leaders have welcomed the attention juan gonzales 
a news columnist calls the strike a decisive battle between 
labor and management in the united states the labor movement 
is drawing a line in the sand this trend of breaking unions is 
going to stop here 
the aflcio has four staffers working in new york and gave the 
news unions 100000 for an advertising and reader boycott campaign 
directed by samuel mcknight a veteran labor lawyer from michigan 
at a rally nov 14 outside the daily news building leaders of 
some of the nations top unions promised the strikers about 
300000 and local unions have pledged 2 million 
if national interest has raised the stakes in the strike some 
wonder if it might also influence the way the strike is conducted 
when management hires replacement workers once a relatively 
rare tactic albeit a legal one unions are reacting with unusual 
bitterness according to filippelli 
in labor disputes such as those at the daily news eastern and 
greyhound a message is being sent to unionized employers that 
unions might be willing to take a company down if replacement 
workers are used he said 
ester fuchs a barnard college professor who specializes in 
urban politics questions such tactics 
because of the boycott the unions are going to be blamed 
rightfully or wrongfully if the paper closes she said 
she also wonders if unions should focus national attention on 
this particular strike if they lose under these circumstances 
people will ask how they can win anywhere else if they win its 
not a cue for anyone elsewhere because the conditions in new york 
are so special 
strike organizers challenge that assessment mcknight the labor 
lawyer said strikes are won by hurting the employer economically 
said filippelli the boycott is aimed at getting a 
settlement and i dont think anyone wants to drive the news out of 
business 
indeed the aflcios hardesty said the strike can showcase 
labors ability to work with management he points to the new york 
post a rival tabloid where unions made extensive wageandhour 
concessions earlier this year 
wed like to say to employers we know we can go down with 
you wed like to go up with you he said 
