<TEXT>
egypt gets to write off billions of dollars in 
debt syria gains more control over lebanon china lands a 50 
million loan the soviet union wins help restructuring its economy 
nations that have joined the usled effort against iraq by 
sending troops to the gulf or agreeing to abstain in a key united 
nations vote are getting a little something in return 
and those who havent may find it a little more difficult to get 
expected aid from the united states and other countries 
in the world of diplomacy there is nothing unusual about a 
little exchange of favors which diplomats call quid pro quo 
but analysts say iraqs invasion of kuwait is pushing 
international politicking to new extremes including highlevel 
us contacts with nations it has accused of supporting terrorism 
syria cuba and soon iraq itself 
altruism and principle do not always make the world go 
round said michael mandelbaum eastwest studies director for 
the council on foreign relations expecting something for your 
support is normal predictable understandable behavior in 
diplomacy and politics 
its difficult to draw a direct link between cooperation in the 
gulf and increased aid some of the benefits such as egyptian debt 
relief and help for the soviets may have come anyway but maybe 
not so expeditiously 
and not all of the aid is coming from the united states 
but washingtons attitude toward a country can make a 
difference 
for example the bush administration called on other wealthy 
countries to help jordan only after king hussein said he would 
apply full sanctions against neighboring iraq 
and after yemen voted against a ussponsored resolution 
authorizing the use of force against iraqi president saddam 
hussein the state department began reviewing american aid to that 
country 
a department source who spoke only on condition of anonymity 
said yemens chance of getting 30 million was now not as strong 
as it might have been 
about twodozen nations are sending troops ships planes or 
other support for the military buildup against saddams 
millionmember army 
other countries have balked at sending troops germany and 
japan cite prohibitions in their constitutions but are helping 
those who do and those who suffer most that also helps keep the 
fragile alliance together 
the us force in the persian gulf is expected to reach 400000 
soldiers in the next few weeks the secondlargest force 144500 
troops is from the area most directly threatened by iraqs 
occupation of kuwait the gulf cooperation council nations of saudi 
arabia bahrain oman united arab emirates qatar and the exiled 
kuwaiti regime 
egypt has pledged 20000 soldiers along with tanks and heavy 
artillery syria which borders iraq to the west has 6500 
soldiers in saudi arabia and a 15000member armored division is to 
be added 
for spearheading arab support egypt is being rewarded in 
washington with a writeoff of 67 billion in loans used to buy 
arms from the united states 
even before iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait us officials 
were looking for a way to relieve egypts financial burden but 
egypts cooperation helped sell the debtforgiveness plan to 
congress 
pakistan has pledged to send 5000 troops to the persian gulf 
and another 5000 serve as advisers with the saudi military 
saudi arabia the united arab emirates and the kuwaiti regime 
are lending about 500 million to pakistan to help compensate for 
oil imports cut off by the gulf crisis according to kuwaiti 
officials 
analysts agree that the soviet union has made clear it wants 
some economic assistance for its support of the saudius 
position 
its an important signal that the soviets voted for the united 
nations sanctions against iraq said jim phillips an analyst for 
the conservative heritage foundation i think they expect food 
aid its a hazy quid pro quo but the soviets are counting on us 
goodwill down the line 
the soviets so far have committed only warships but indicate 
they would send ground forces under a un command in return 
saudi arabia and other arab nations aligned against iraq reportedly 
are putting together a multibilliondollar loan package for moscow 
other countries sending troops include britain with 30000 
france with 13000 morocco with 1200 and bangladesh with 
2000 
the support from some nations has been bare bones and clearly 
aimed more at showing the flag in an international operation and 
warming relations with the united states than seriously aiding the 
military effort 
italy the netherlands spain australia argentina canada 
greece denmark norway and portugal all have sent ships to the 
gulf but have stopped short of committing significant ground 
forces 
new zealand which has been at odds with washington since the 
wellington government banned nuclearpower submarines in 1984 
pledged two planes and a medical team 
other countries receiving or looking for more us aid also are 
kicking in token support czechoslovakia is sending a 200man army 
unit and poland a military field hospital the philippines is 
putting together a medical team 
for china it was enough just not to say no 
during backstage negotiations leading up to the security 
councils vote allowing military action the asian development bank 
granted china a 50 million agricultural loan it was the first 
loan by the usinfluenced bank to beijing since the june 1989 
crackdown on student demonstrators 
china which could have stopped the resolution with its veto 
abstained when the council voted the day after the loan was 
announced 
then chinese foreign minister qian qichen was welcomed in 
washington for meetings with bush and his aides ending an 18month 
ban on highlevel contacts with china 
chinese officials denied that they used the un veto power to 
gain political favors and bank officials refused to comment on 
whether the loan was linked to the un resolution 
