<TEXT>
a year after police put 51 vietnamese on a 
plane to hanoi in the only forced repatriation of boat people 
pressure is mounting to resume the controversial policy 
british colonial officials say forced repatriation eventually 
will be seen as the only way to clear hong kongs squalid camps of 
tens of thousands of refugees whatever the international outcry 
that accompanies it 
if hong kong resumes the policy united nations officials 
predict other countries in the region will follow suit returning 
more than 100000 vietnamese who crowd camps throughout asia 
once back in vietnam no one can protect the wouldbe refugees 
from persecution the united nations which monitors boat people 
who return voluntarily says it can do nothing to help those who 
are forced to return because it opposes the policy 
early next year the government will consider lifting a 
moratorium imposed on mandatory repatriation said clinton leeks 
hong kongs refugee coordinator 
its really our only option he said in an interview 
leeks said western governments are not taking enough of the 
genuine refugees and the number of boat people deemed to be 
nonrefugees or economic migrants is growing 
human rights lawyers say they look to the united states the 
sole remaining western country actively opposed to forcing 
vietnamese home as a last line of defense 
the us is the only thing that stands between the boat people 
and prison planes or prison ships back to vietnam said david j 
clark a law professor at the university of hong kong who has 
studied the boat people problem 
american officials insist that us opposition to forced 
repatriation remains staunch but analysts agree that washingtons 
policy is linked to its refusal to normalize relations with 
vietnam 
if vietnam helps organize elections in cambodia and participates 
in settling the cambodian civil war us diplomats say the united 
states may recognize hanoi by 1992 
the next day look for forced repatriation a us official 
said on condition of anonymity 
in the camps of tin huts concrete and watchtowers the 
prospects are depressing to hong kongs 52171 boat people 
wed rather die that go back to vietnam reads a sign stuck 
on a chainlink fence at whitehead detention center the biggest of 
hong kongs 15 camps 
a yearend report by a western consulate predicted riots and 
bloodshed in the camps if the dec 12 1989 forced repatriation is 
repeated 
the americans should know what kind of resistance the people 
from north vietnam are capable of mounting a police official 
said 
a un official who works in the camps said he believes the 
vietnamese know they are fighting a losing battle 
forced repatriation could become unnecessary he said if the 
vietnamese realize they have no place to go but home un 
officials have begun telling the refugees since october they should 
return home a radical break with previous policy 
since the vietnam war ended in 1975 more than 15 million 
vietnamese have fled since the vietnam war ended in april 1975 the 
united states has accepted almost 1 million indochinese refugees 
about three times the total of the next three countries 
australia canada and france 
as a place of first refuge hong kong has borne the brunt of the 
exodus 162479 arrivals since 1979 but the numbers are declining 
only 6201 boat people have arrived so far this year compared 
with 34114 in 1989 resettlements rose to 7152 a 50 percent 
increase from 1989 
hope for a solution increased in september when vietnam the 
united nations and britain signed an agreement creating a new 
category of boat people those who do not oppose repatriation 
to supplement voluntary repatriation 
