<TEXT>
the danes who claim the worlds 
record in parliamentary elections reluctantly vote again 
wednesday and the hottest issue seems to be who provoked the 
unwanted balloting 
conservative prime minister poul schlueter blames an economic 
dispute with the opposition for forcing his election call 
even he reflects the countrys lack of enthusiasm for its 20th 
general parliamentary vote in 45 years shlueter says he wants to 
get it over with as soon as possible 
denmark has one of the worlds most fractured democracies it 
has not had a majority government since 1971 longer than any other 
pluralistic system 
schlueter whose centerright coalition controls just 67 seats 
in the 179seat parliament has called four elections since 1982 
the latest campaign lacks the trappings seen in those held most 
other countries 
there are no mass rallies in the streets the size and placement 
of campaign posters is severely restricted by law paid political 
spots are not accepted on state radio or on the two public tv 
channels 
yet turnout among denmarks 39million electorate averaging 85 
percent since 1945 is among the worlds best 
thirteen parties ranging from marxists to antitax crusaders are 
competing for the vote with just 2 percent of the vote needed for 
representation many gain seats and have emerged as kingmakers 
between the evenly balanced main parties 
political scientist steen sauerberg says many danish follow 
the liberal ideal of giving the little guy a chance too 
another reason for the frequent votes he says is because there 
are no fixed terms for parliamentarians although there is a 
fouryear maximum 
schlueter whose coalition includes the liberals and social 
liberals called the vote to settle a minor dispute with the main 
opposition social democrats on economic policy and taxes 
both sides wanted a 6 percent cut at the top of the progressive 
tax scale but the social democrats opposed financing it with 
reductions in social benefits 
unlike in the neighboring scandinavian countries of sweden and 
norway the two main political blocs in denmark have remained 
evenly balanced neither the left nor right has managed to get a 
working majority said sauerberg 
this allows the small parties often to hold the balance of power 
in the parliament he added 
but danish politics despite its surface chaos remains 
surprisingly stable 
the voters tend to stay loyal to their party and support for 
the parties swings only a few percentage points after each 
election said sauerberg 
all 13 parties get equal time on tv to present their political 
platforms regardless of their current strength they also 
participate in a series of debates among all the parties at once 
the basic flaw in the current campaigns says sauerberg is that 
the politicians spend more time speculating openly about possible 
coalitions than they do discussing the traditional issues of 
employment taxes and welfare 
so why do the danes keep voting 
simply because of the danes sense of duty towards society and 
the fact that voter registration is automatic you get a card in 
the mail sauerberg said 
