<TEXT>
former gov deane c davis who pushed 
through legislation to protect vermonts environment has died at 
age 90 
the twoterm republican who served from 1969 to 1973 died 
saturday at central vermont hospital in berlin of complications 
from gall bladder surgery 
the scion of a farming family davis a lawyer had neither 
served in the legislature nor held statewide elective office when 
he ran for governor in 1968 
in 1970 davis had one of the most successful legislative 
sessions ever enjoyed by a vermont governor 
legislators enacted a pioneering law that controlled major 
development projects by establishing how they would be evaluated 
an innovative water quality law and legislation restructuring the 
government into superagencies 
in april 1970 davis presided over vermonts first greenup day 
a project to clean up the state more than 70000 people helped 
remove 4000 truckloads of trash from interstate highways 
at age 9 davis became a member of the first boy scout troop in 
america 
in 1940 he served as general counsel for the national life 
insurance co in montpelier ten years later he became president of 
the company which he helped build into one of the biggest firms in 
the nation 
in retirement he wrote two books of vermont humor his memoirs 
are scheduled to be published in the spring 
davis first wife corrine died of cancer in 1952 he married 
marjorie smith conzelman 
davis is survived by his wife a son a daughter and a sister 
a funeral is scheduled for wednesday 
