president vaclav havel asked 
parliament today for broader temporary powers to keep the country 
from breaking apart 
in an emergency speech he said czechoslovakias future is being 
threatened by a dispute over a division of powers between the 
federal government the czech republic and the slovak republic 
where nationalism has risen rapidly 
i am very sorry i had to go this far the 
playwrightturnedpresident said in the nationally televised 
speech i am doing this to fulfill the expectations of millions 
of citizens who entrusted this position to me and believe i 
will help save our federation 
our state is not this time threatened from the outside as so 
many times in the past but from the inside he said we are 
threatening it ourselves with ou low political culture lack of 
democratic consciousness and mututal understanding our lack of 
experience and personal bad qualities 
havel did not immediately say what powers he wants he said they 
would be included in a bill to be presented soon to parliament and 
he urged that it be considered immediately 
he said the powers would be in effect until a new constitution 
is adopted sometime within the next 18 months 
havel also proposed that parliament immediately set up a 
constitutional court and pass a law permitting national referenda 
as last resorts to settle political disputes 
under czechoslovakias current constitution havel is empowered 
to sign treaties command the armed forces appoint the federal 
government summon and dissolve parliament sign its laws grant 
amnesties or other legal pardons and declare war 
he is also allowed to assume extra powers granted by special 
law 
havel has been content for much of his nearly one year as 
president to be a moral force in politics but his tough speech 
today before parliament indicated that separatist threats from the 
slovak republic had forced him to act 
he singled out the premier of the slovak republic vladimir 
meciar for criticism 
slovak leaders have been quoted as saying that if the federal 
parliament insists on amending a draft agreement dividing powers 
among the federal government and the republics they will declare 
the sovereignty of slovak law on their territory 
parliament plans tuesday to debate a law dividing powers among 
the federal government and the two republics 
the czech and slovak parliaments differ over control of oil and 
gas pipelines taxation and budget questions postal services 
control over policy toward ethnic minorities and chairmanship of 
the national bank 
havel said a declaration of slovak sovereignty was clearly 
unconstitutional and said that whatever decision parliament makes 
is legally binding on all institutions and all people 
otherwise the thin ice of our constitution will be broken and 
our state would inevitably fall into legal chaos he said 
he warned that if czechoslovakia formed from two parts of the 
former austrohungarian empire in 1918 broke in two neither part 
could guarantee the inviolability of its borders and chances for 
economic reform would end 
western leaders repeatedly have warned czechoslovakia that its 
internal instability is one of the greatest threats to aid and 
investment 
czechoslovakia needs large amounts of both to throw off the 
vestiges of four decades of communism government economic policy 
calls for rapid privatization of the staterun economy beginning 
next year 
