john alexander a former metropolitan opera 
tenor and professor of music at the university of cincinnati died 
after a performance in his hometown of meridian miss he was 67 
alexander suffered a heart attack saturday shortly after 
finishing a performance of nessum dorma from turandot he 
died later saturday at anderson hospital in meridian 
he had been in meridian the city where he was born for a gala 
benefit for the restoration of the communitys 100yearold opera 
house 
everyone here is amazed at the poeticness of his death 
said his soninlaw david staples of chicago he was doing a 
major performance for the first time in three years he was with 
his friends from the world of opera and was back in mississippi 
which he loved and where he always wanted to be buried in his 
familys plot 
alexander began his career in cincinnati as a student at the old 
cincinnati conservatory of music his debut was the lead in 
faust at the cincinnati summer opera at the zoo in 1950 
he had a long career at the new york city opera and the 
metropolitan opera where he sang for 25 years he was known for 
his moaart roles including belmonte in the abduction from the 
seraglio and ferrando in cosi fan tutte he was acclaimed at 
both new york houses as bacchus is strausss ariadne auf naxos 
alexander had two heart bypass operations in the 1970s but 
continued to perform at the metropolitan until 1987 he still 
taught opera and voice at the conservatory now part of the 
university of cincinnati and gave occasional performances he 
lived with his wife sue in suburban cincinnati 
he was always interested in young people mrs alexander 
said he was an unselfish outgoing and loving person and always 
the tenor 
italo tajo retired chairman of the conservatorys opera 
department said alexanders death will be a loss to the music 
world 
he was a great asset to any theater because he was always 
ready for anything tajo said 
alexander had sung leading roles in more than 50 operas he was 
on the board of trustees of the cincinnati opera company 
in addition to his wife survivors include a daughter cindy 
staples of chicago a sister ann quin of jackson miss and two 
grandchildren 
funeral services are scheduled tuesday in meridian 
