<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to postpone a 
jan 22 election under a redistricting plan designed to help elect 
an hispanic to the los angeles county board of supervisors for the 
first time in 115 years 
the court rejected an emergency request by board members who 
said the plan ordered by a federal judge is unlawful 
the justices oowever took no action on a formal appeal by 
board members still pending before the high court 
the fivemember board controlled by conservatives was accused 
by hispanics in 1988 of violating their rights by drawing districts 
after the 1980 census that allegedly diluted hispanic voting 
strength 
the lawsuit against the board said the district lines violated 
constitutional rights assuring equal protection for all and a 1982 
federal voting rights law the law forbids not only intentional 
discrimination but also any practice that has the effect of 
weakening the voting strength of minorities 
us district judge david v kenyon declared the former district 
plan unconstitutional he carved out a new district in which 
hispanics account for an estimated 51 percent of the registered 
voters and 71 percent of the population 
kenyon ruled that when the board redrew districts after the 1980 
census members fragmented the hispanic vote in an effort to help 
their own reelection chances 
the number of hispanics living in what constitutes the district 
created by kenyon has increased dramatically in the last decade 
the board member now representing the new district is retiring 
the county has a population of about 85 million people and the 
board of supervisors has considerable power over such matters as 
planning and development 
the bush administration sided with hispanic rights groups in 
urging the supreme court not to disturb kenyons ruling which was 
upheld last month by the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
the cases are los angeles county vs garza 90849 a422 
</TEXT>
