<TEXT>
the supreme court today asked the bush 
administration for its views on whether a civil war era law enacted 
primarily to protect freed slaves bans racially discriminatory 
firings 
the justices said they want to hear from justice department 
lawyers about a ruling that the manufacturer of buster brown shoes 
was guilty of illegal racial bias when it fired a white supervisor 
at a missouri warehouse 
the court is not expected to say whether it will review the case 
until hearing from the government lawyers which could take months 
kenneth hicks worked for the brown shoe company for 34 years 
his assignment when fired in 1982 had been as evening shift foreman 
at a warehouse in benton mo 
the company in trimming its workforce dismissed hicks while 
keeping another supervisor alvin chester who is black 
hicks said he was fired because of his race even though he had 
more seniority than chester 
hicks testified that when he asked a boss at the warehouse if 
race was behind the firing the boss smirked and said you said 
that not me 
hicks also cited evidence that the company had an affirmative 
action plan aimed at promoting more blacks to supervisory jobs 
company officials said they chose to retain chester because he 
had more experience and was better qualified for the specific job 
both men were doing 
a federal jury ordered the company to pay hicks 10000 in 
punitive damages and the 8th us circuit court of appeals in 
april awarded him nearly 21000 more in attorney fees and other 
legal costs 
the appeals court said a civil rights law enacted in 1866 
forbids racially discriminatory firings 
the law was the focus of a highly publicized supreme court 
ruling in 1989 
the justices said the law does not ban onthejob racial 
harassment but they upheld a 1976 ruling that the law does permit 
lawsuits against private individuals or companies accused of bias 
in the making and enforcing of contracts 
left unanswered was whether the law specifically applies to 
racially biased firings 
the 8th circuit court said last years high court ruling is 
unclear adding we simply decline to overrule the clear and 
undisputed precedent of this circuit 
the appeals court with jurisdiction in seven midwestern states 
said firing is fundamentally different from racial harassment or 
discrimination in the terms or conditions of employment 
discriminatory discharge goes to the very existence and nature of 
the employment contract 
the states in the 8th circuit are arkansas iowa minnesota 
missouri nebraska north dakota and south dakota 
the case is brown group inc vs hicks 90324 
</TEXT>
