<TEXT>
the supreme court agreed today to decide 
whether prison inmates sometimes are entitled to jury trials when 
suing prison officials over alleged mistreatment 
the justices said it will hear an appeal by john j mccarthy 
who accused officials at a state prison in somers conn of 
violating his rights when they removed him from his cell in 1983 
he said officials used excessive force in using tear gas to get 
him out of his cell he also alleged that they planted a knife in 
his cell as a pretext for removing him 
mccarthy initially agreed to have a federal magistrate decide 
his case but later changed his mind 
us district judge jose a cabranes ruled that mccarthy had 
given up his right to a jury trial and assigned the case to 
magistrate f owen eagan 
the magistrate after conducting eight days of hearings at the 
prison in 1988 recommended that cabranes rule in favor of the 
prison officials and the judge agreed 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld the judges ruling 
the appeals court said cabranes acted properly in rejecting 
mccarthys request to have a jury decide the case against the 
officials 
federal law authorizes federal judges to assign to magistrates 
cases in which prisoners say their rights are violated by 
conditions of confinement the judge can designate a magistrate 
even if the officials and prisoners object 
the supreme court said it will decide whether the same rule 
applies when a prisoner alleges a specific episode of allegedly 
unconstitutional conduct rather than continuing prison 
conditions 
the case is mccarthy vs bronson 905635 
</TEXT>
