<TEXT>
serbias ruling communists and their 
hardline president slobodan milosevic were headed monday for an 
election victory that could split yugoslavia apart 
as official returns trickled in from serbias first free ballot 
since 1938 the renamed socialists and milosevic took a commanding 
lead over their main challengers the centerright nationalist 
serbian renewal movement 
a victory for milosevic and his party is almost certain to 
deepen the rift between serbia and the prowestern republics of 
croatia and slovenia where centerright parties ousted communists 
in spring elections 
the opposition charged the communists with widespread 
voterigging international observers said they believed sundays 
election was essentially fair but indicated communist domination 
of serbias media made for a biased campaign 
in montenegro communists were already celebrating what they 
claimed to be an overwhelming victory over 10 opposition parties 
according to unofficial returns reported by the state tanjug news 
agency 
tanjug said the communist candidate for montenegros presidency 
momir bulatovic appeared as likely as milosevic to win outright 
without being forced into a runoff 
a runoff vote will be held dec 23 for any of the 250 parliament 
seats in serbia or 125 seats in montenegro in constituencies where 
no single candidate wins 50 percent 
all i can say is they are leading and leading well jova 
vukelic spokesman for the serbian democratic party said of 
milosevics socialists vukelic said he based his comment on 
partial results reaching his party 
tanjug said the socialists had won nearly 80 seats in the 
serbian parliament according to an unofficial survey of 140 out of 
250 districts 
initial results indicate that the communists will have at 
least a 60 percent majority over the opposition in parliament 
said dragan veselinov president of the opposition peasants party 
we should be happy if they win only 60 percent im afraid 
they could win by an even higher margin said vojislav kostunica 
of the democratic party 
the outcome of the vote in serbia is likely to decide whether 
this volatile balkan country stays together or breaks up 
the newly elected governments in slovenia and croatia advocate 
greater democracy and have threatened to secede if yugoslavias 
federation of six republics does not transform into a loose 
confederation of nearindependent states 
milosevic has refused to acknowledge the possibility of a 
federal breakup or to negotiate with the western republics 
his main rival for president vuk draskovic of the serbian 
renewal movement has said he would negotiate with croatia and 
slovenia 
electoral commission chairman caslav ignjatovic said he was 
investigating claims of ballotrigging and widespread 
irregularities at the serbian republics 9500 polling stations 
draskovic said the socialists distributed campaign leaflets at 
polling stations sunday and that progovernment media also ignored 
a ban on campaigning 48 hours before the election 
opposition leaders also claimed the socialists stopped 
registering deaths in serbia in april and rigged the election 
using phantom votes 
in terms of procedures at individual voting places the 
elections passed fairly well said robert hand an official of 
the conference on security and cooperation in europe which 
monitored the serbian elections 
our main concern is what happened before the elections hand 
said he said the group was unhappy with the limited opposition 
access to the communistcontrolled media during the campaign 
serbias statecontrolled media claimed the opposition parties 
were prowestern enemies of the republic whose victory could lead 
to civil war with other yugoslav regions 
the divisions among serbs croats and slovenes reflect the babel 
of ethnic and political forces vying for power in yugoslavia the 
us central intelligence agency predicted recently that the 
country could be torn apart within 18 months and said civil war was 
possible 
