<TEXT>
a top federal safety official called monday 
for a national campaign to persuade 21 remaining states to pass 
laws to immediately 
confiscate the licenses of drivers who fail or refuse 
drunkendriving tests 
james l kolstad chairman of the national transportation safety 
board told a meeting of the national commission on drunk driving 
that license confiscation is a simple direct and inexpensive 
way to attack a problem blamed for 60 deaths a day or nearly 22000 
fatalities a year 
such laws already have been passed by 29 states and the district 
of columbia and kolstad said they have resulted in substantial 
decreases of drunken driving 
kolstad noted that the deaths of eight persons in the collision 
of two northwest airlines passenger jets at detroit metropolitan 
airport a week ago flashed across the tv screens and the front 
pages of our newspapers 
and almost immediately the calls for corrective action to 
prevent that kind of accident from happening again were heard he 
said 
he said that while the response was understandable and correct 
it is disappointing that society does not get equally concerned 
when transportation deaths occur on our nations roads and 
highways 
drunk driving is one of the leading causes of death in our 
country today and it is totally preventable kolstad said 
kolstad noted that a recent safety board study found that a 
third of fatally injured truck drivers tested positive for alcohol 
or drugs 
four out of five of these drivers had a history of substance 
abuse before their fatal accidents he said 
kolstads proposal recently listed as one of the safety boards 
mostwanted safety changes would require the immediate 
confiscation of a license if a driver either fails a sobriety test 
or refuses to take one 
under the program a driver is given a temporary license and 
given the option of an administrative hearing 
that hearing establishes only one basic fact did the driver 
indeed fail the test or refuse to take it kolstad said if the 
answer is yes the drivers license is revoked on the spot 
the driver may still face criminal charges later but the 
important result is that they are taken off the road in very short 
order he said there are no appeals no dilatory tactics no 
mitigating circumstances no plea bargaining no pretrial 
diversion the drunk driver is taken off the road 
this approach works and it works well he said adding that 
it deters not only drivers found drunk behind the wheel but also 
those who have not been caught but who will fear losing their 
driving privileges 
kolstad urged a lobbying campaign to convince legislators and 
governors of the common sense necessity of administrative license 
revocation laws 
according to the safety board the 21 states which have not 
passed such laws are alabama arkansas georgia idaho kentucky 
massachusetts michigan montana nebraska new hampshire new 
jersey new york ohio pennsylvania rhode island south carolina 
south dakota tennessee texas virginia and washington 
</TEXT>
