<TEXT>
the supreme court indicated interest monday in 
an important civil rights issue whether a civil warera law 
enacted primarily to protect freed slaves bans racially 
discriminatory firings 
the justices asked the bush administration for its views on the 
issue urging justice department lawyers to comment on a ruling 
that the manufacturer of buster brown shoes was guilty of illegal 
racial bias when it fired a white supervisor at a missouri 
warehouse 
after hearing from the government lawyers which could be months 
away the court will decide whether it wants to hear the case 
kenneth hicks a white foreman with the brown shoe company was 
fired in 1982 after 34 years with the firm 
the company in trimming its work force dismissed hicks while 
keeping another supervisor alvin chester who is black 
hicks said he was fired because of his race even though he had 
more seniority than chester 
the shoe company asked the high court to overturn rulings in 
favor of hicks who was awarded 10000 in punitive damages and 
nearly 21000 more in attorney fees 
the supreme court in a highly publicized ruling in 1989 on the 
civil warera law left unanswered whether the act specifically 
applies to racially biased firings 
the law at issue was enacted in 1866 and provides that all 
persons shall have the same rightto make and enforce 
contracts and to the full and equal benefit of all laws 
enjoyed by white citizens 
the 1964 civil rights law offers similar protection but the 
older statute authorizes broader remedies particularly punitive 
damages 
in another civil rights case monday the court refused to 
postpone a jan 22 election under a redistricting plan designed to 
help elect a hispanic to the los angeles county board of 
supervisors for the first time in 115 years 
the court rejected an emergency request by board members who 
said the plan ordered by a federal judge is unlawful 
but the justices took no action on a formal appeal by board 
members still pending before the high court 
the fivemember board was accused by hispanics in 1988 of 
violating their rights by drawing districts after the 1980 census 
that allegedly diluted hispanic voting strength 
us district judge david v kenyon declared the former district 
plan unconstitutional and carved out a new district in which 
hispanics account for an estimated 51 percent of the registered 
voters and 71 percent of the population 
the bush administration sided with hispanic rights groups in 
urging the supreme court not to disturb kenyons ruling which was 
upheld last month by the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
</TEXT>
