<TEXT>
pakistan completed a nationwide 
census on monday and analysts say the new rightwing government 
has little time to find a way to cope with the nations soaring 
birthrate 
conservative estimates put pakistans current population at 
about 120 million almost 40 million more than in 1980 
at that rate family planning experts say the population will 
double by the year 2020 
this was the first census in a decade in pakistan one of the 
worlds fastestgrowing countries census takers had been going 
from tents to driedmud houses to palatial mansions since nov 22 
by the time the results are released in about six months 
hundreds of thousands of children will have been born the 
burgeoning population threatens to devour the countrys already 
meager resources 
pakistan a predominantly moslem nation produces a child every 
eight seconds observers say that kind of growth could lead to 
economic collapse 
if they dont deal with this soon theyll be facing a 
disaster in five to 10 years its a nightmare that nobody wants 
said one western diplomat who asked not to be identified 
pakistans birthrate stands at 32 percent well ahead of the 2 
percent in india its neighbor to the east so far there is little 
evidence the new government is eager to embark on an ambitious 
family planning program 
the social services ministry responsible for encouraging small 
families in pakistan is headed by a fundamentalist moslem saddar 
niazi who boasts of being one of 15 children 
he said the pressure for family planning is a holdover from the 
liberal secularism of former prime minister benazir bhutto who was 
ousted aug 6 on charges of corruption and ineffectiveness and 
overwhelmingly defeated in national elections three months later 
most pakistani women have an average of six to seven children 
the highest fertility rate in asia and only 11 percent of couples 
of childbearing age use contraceptives 
most rural women are veiled at puberty and bartered into 
marriage as early as 15 most women have at least four living 
children by the time they turn 30 almost as many would have died 
at childbirth or before the age of five 
proponents of family planning struggle against conservative 
views of islamic clerics when women consider birth control they 
are often chastised for defying what is called gods grand design 
the national institute of population studies has warned that 
even if pakistan became a nation of twochild families the 
population would grow to 160 million in the next several decades 
just to keep the current standard of living we must double 
all our infrastructure hospitals schools housing food 
production water resources and factories said spokesman 
mohammad sheikh 
pakistans infrastructure is dilapidated health care is 
inadequate and available only in the cities and towns 
khurshed ahmed a senator and member of the ultraorthodox 
jamaatiislami or party of god said there was no need for family 
planning education and affluence would check population growth he 
said 
but pakistan is desperately short of schools 
more than 52 percent of pakistans budget is spent on defense 
and a meager 4 percent on education less than 17 percent of the 
population as a whole can read or write and the percentage is far 
smaller for women 
