andras until recently slovak interior minister was alluding to 
the authoritarian communist rule 
czechoslovakia formally became a federation in 1968 but 
hardline communist rule meant slovaks felt controlled by prague 
the czech and federal capital czechs meanwhile resented the 
allocation of half the countrys resources to just one third of its 
people the approximately 5 million slovaks 
czechoslovakia is embarking on an ambitious reform program in 
which the stateowned economy will be turned over to private hands 
but western leaders repeatedly have warned that political 
instability will hamper the foreign investment and aid that the 
economy badly needs 
a law dividing powers among the federal government and the two 
republics was to be debated by parliament on tuesday when havel 
was scheduled to leave on a visit to spain and portugal 
the bill on presidential powers was to be debated later that 
leaves the issue of strong new presidential powers hanging over 
deputies while they discuss dividing government functions 
the czech and slovak parliaments differ over control of oil and 
gas pipelines taxation and budget questions postal services 
control over policy toward ethnic minorities and chairmanship of 
the national bank 
an agreement forged last month between the czech slovak and 
federal governments keeps foreign policy defense general economic 
and monetary policy under federal control 
to prolonged applause from parliament havel stressed that 
sovereignty of slovak law on slovak territory would be 
unconstitutional the federal parliaments decisions should be 
binding on all institutions and on all people he said 
otherwise the thin ice of our constitution will be broken and 
our state would inevitably fall into legal chaos he said 
