federal regulators on monday lifted an 
evacuation order imposed on a flooded subdivision after 
cancercausing pcbs were discovered in the oily floodwater 
the decision allowed residents forced from 120 homes near the 
little calumet river to return to assess flood damage and gather 
personal belongings six inches of rain late last month left the 
420home wicker park manor subdivision under five feet of water 
polychlorinated biphenyls once used as insulators in electrical 
transformers were banned by the federal government in the 1970s 
the main eastwest street through the subdivision became a 
dividing line wednesday after the environmental protection agency 
detected double the acceptable safe limit of pcbs in the 
floodwater 
residents living north of the street were banned from returning 
to their homes while other residents were granted access the 
source of the pcbs is not known 
the entire subdivision was closed friday while epa testers 
broadened the scope of their sampling to areas south of the street 
a growing number of residents were permitted to return through 
sunday as followup tests showed no detectable levels of pcbs in 
homes heating oil soil or debris said epa spokesman philip 
schuette 
the negative test results suggest the epa may have trouble 
finding the origin of the contamination he said 
