<TEXT>
the government on monday began 
transfering home hundreds of southern sudanese who had been living 
in shantytowns around the capital hoping to escape a civil war and 
food shortage 
a train carrying 619 displaced people took off monday for the 
western town of babanousa where the passengers will be transported 
by road to their homes in southern sudan the official sudan news 
agency said 
the agency quoted brig mohamed osman the governor of the 
capital khartoum as saying the reasons behind their displacement 
have now disappeared and urged the returnees to go back home and 
start producing their own food 
the displaced people poured in over the past few years setting 
up shantytowns around khartoum to escape the civil war in the south 
and the subsequent food shortages 
the agency said the passengers all left on their own free will 
it said the government has arranged for trains to move them out of 
khartoum every two weeks 
the government has denied earlier claims that it was forcing the 
displaced people to return to the wartorn south 
in other parts of sudan authorities are discouraging the 
establishment of refugee camps where thousands have recently 
arrived escaping a famine the government is apparently trying to 
avoid a repetition of sudans 198485 tragedy when thousands died 
in camps from lack of adequate food and medicines 
thousands of people fleeing hunger in the western region of 
kordofan arrived at a camp near the regional capital elobeid 
they are to be given a months supply of food and sent home 
a drought and consequent famine have struck most of the country 
affecting up to 7 million of its 25 million people and worse is 
expected within six months 
