small hills of bagged garbage began to crowd 
sidewalks in parts of manhattan on monday the first day of a 
strike by workers employed by private haulers 
residential garbage collection is performed by the new york city 
sanitation department and was not affected by the strike if 
accumulating garbage becomes a health or fire hazard however the 
agency will make emergency pickups 
a 2100member teamsters local called the strike after union 
members rejected a new contract raising wages 70 over three years 
the workers now earn 600 to 700 a week and sought a 90 raise 
union leader bernard adelstein said the strike was generally 
effective in all five city boroughs although in the bronx a few 
trucks went out with scabs 
salvatore spinelli a spokesman for the private carters said 
about 30 percent of trucks were operating throughout the city 
staffed by management and nonstriking crews some replacement 
workers might also have been hired he said 
about 400 private carters collect 10000 tons of garbage daily 
from 250000 business and commercial sites in new york city 
at least one hauler hired security guards to follow his trucks 
on their route in case of trouble but police spokesman detective 
joseph mcconville said no strikerelated violence was reported 
no talks were scheduled both sides said the next step was up to 
the citys labor negotiator eric schmertz who has been working on 
the dispute 
on monday the most conspicuous uncollected piles of garbage were 
in midtown manhattan mostly on side streets by fastfood outlets 
large movie theaters and restaurants with high turnover 
if health or fire inspectors decide the uncollected garbage is 
dangerous city sanitation crews will pick it up and charge the 
customers 1470 per cubic yard thats the rate the city permits 
private carters to charge 
consumer affairs commissioner mark green whose agency regulates 
hauling rates has recommended that the current fee be cut by about 
1 a cubic yard 
both the union and the private carters accused green of helping 
precipitate the strike 
green said the workers and employers could search for 
scapegoats but any failure in their negotiation is not due to my 
rate 
new york citys private garbage collectors a 1 billion service 
industry were last struck for 17 days in 1981 
