<TEXT>
a century after her poems were 
published reclusive poet emily dickinson is getting the 
publication party she never had and the kind of thing she probably 
would have hated 
i guess were safe in doing it at this time observed martha 
ackmann an organizer of mondays celebration commemorating the 
publication of the bulk of dickinsons poetry 100 years ago the 
publication came four years after the poets death 
the poet might have deplored the fuss but ackmann said her old 
college is just making up for lost time 
we kind of think of it as the publication party mount holyoke 
never gave emily dickinson an acknowledgement of her 
achievement said ackmann assistant professor of womens studies 
and english at the allwomen school 
about three dozen dickinson devotees gathered monday afternoon 
for a lecture and poetry accompanied by punch and gingerbread 
their reasons for attending varied 
i always liked her poetry for one thing said sarah rusk 
who has lived in south hadley for 50 years 
amherst college senior josh jacobs who came to brush up on the 
poet said he thinks dickinson would probably have lived an 
isolated life in any age 
even now when you think about the industry which seeks so 
persistently to discover people it seems to me that the way she 
lived there could be someone like her today who wont be 
published till 2130 he said 
the enigma of dickinson how she could have been content to see 
only eight of her poems published during her lifetime and those 
anonymosly lies at the heart of the celebration 
the question ive always wanted to ask emily dickinson herself 
is how did she keep going what made her keep working working 
working at it that must have been an enormous respect for art 
ackmann said 
an inability to stop making revisions and a disdain for the 
vulgarities of fame are two possible explanations for dickinsons 
reticence 
in the 19th century a successful author was the equivalent of 
a 20thcentury rock star ackmann said that would have opened 
her life up to public consideration and scrutiny and i dont think 
that she wanted that 
she was ambivalent at best about publishing said jane 
crosthwaite an associate professor of religion and coorganizer of 
the commemoration at mount holyoke which dickinson attended from 
1847 to 1848 
born 160 years ago monday into a welltodo family dickinson 
often sent poems to friends and family but showed no inclination 
to publish ackmann said 
legend has it that she always wore white and toward the end of 
her life rarely left her house and garden 
after her death in 1886 her sister lavinia was clearing out 
dickinsons rooms when she opened up a bottom drawer of a dresser 
and discovered sheet upon sheet upon sheet upon sheet of poems 
ackmann said 
lavinia showed the poems to some friends and family and then 
arranged for their publication on nov 12 1890 by a boston 
publishing firm called roberts bros ackmann said 
the first 500 copies were well received and a second book was 
published the following year 
publication of the poems often written in an unfinished form 
with perhaps six different adjectives stacked on top of one word 
was not completed until the mid1950s 
ackmann and crosthwaite said they dont believe dickinson would 
have regretted her lost celebrity 
she said that if fame were to come to her it would come she 
might be rather relieved that she didnt have to confront either 
the good or the bad readers of her poetry crosthwaite said i 
dont think she wants to be part of the industry 
