<DOCNO> AP901210-0176 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
nearly half of the nations black children 
live in poverty and the youngest are the worst off a black 
research organization said monday 
the joint center for political and economic studies said black 
children under 3 tend to live in families headed by women in their 
20s who have never married and have few marriage or job prospects 
if current trends hold these children will be increasingly 
hard pressed to overcome the burdens imposed by poverty the 
center said growing numbers of them will not succeed 
cynthia rexroat a clemson university sociologist who is the 
author of the study said the youngest children are even more 
likely to be risk than are the older 
of all black children the study said 465 percent were in 
poverty in 1984 the study said 
ms rexroat said children younger than 3 in families headed by 
nevermarried women had the highest poverty rate of all 87 percent 
in 1984 compared with 76 percent in 1979 she said nearly 
twothirds of these women were in their 20s 
i would expect these trends would hold up as the 1990 census 
data become available she said 
belinda tucker acting director of the center for afroamerican 
studies at the university of california at los angeles said 
sociological projections indicate 30 percent of black women born in 
the early 1950s will never marry 
according to our research black americans value marriage as 
highly as any other ethnic group she said there is mounting 
evidence that limited employment prospects account for much of the 
decline in marriage 
she said increased homicide and crime rates among young black 
men were adding to the problem 
rationally why would any young woman marry a young man who 
stands a pretty good chance of either going to jail or being killed 
and has no job prospects anyway ms tucker asked 
james stewart vice provost and associate professor at 
pennsylvania state university said one of the factors that 
contributes to the stagnant status of nevermarried young women is 
the ineffectiveness of the schooling they have experienced over the 
last 15 years 
it is in part the decline in the quality of education and the 
ability to translate the education that they have into occupations 
that allow them t move out of poverty stewart said 
the study painted the economic picture for black americans as a 
study in contrasts 
on the one hand there is a growing middle class that has made 
great strides toward closing the gap between blacks and whites with 
respect to education employment and therefore economic resources 
and stability it said 
at the same time a growing segment of the black population is 
increasingly mired in poverty 
the study was discussed at a conference sponsored by the center 
which conducts research with the aim of improving the lot of black 
americans 
using data from the 1980 census ms rexroat concluded that the 
average black child who lives with a nevermarried mother will 
spend 15 childhood years in poverty 
the situation was brightest in the south where the poverty rate 
for black children declined from 43 to 37 percent between 1969 and 
1979 it rose only in atlanta birmingham ala and jacksonville 
fla among 25 southern cities studied 
the deepening of poverty for black children was most pronounced 
in the midwest where 37 percent of all black children relied on 
public assistance in 1984 this was nearly double the 20 percent 
figure of 1979 
in 20 metropolitan areas outside the south poverty increased 
among black children on an average of 30 percent to 35 percent from 
1969 to 1979 the study said it said the percentage on welfare 
increased by 11 points in milwaukee and cincinnati and by 10 points 
in buffalo 
the report called for comprehensive strategies and programs to 
improve the quality of education provide skills training for the 
jobs of the future and ensure equal access to employment 
opportunities 
</TEXT>
