few are the economic commentators who havent 
agreed by now that the economy is in recession why hold out with 
layoffs rising retailers forced to cut prices housing and car 
sales down banks in trouble 
but some people not only wont use the r word treating it 
as they would a publicly unutterable reference and most of them 
are associated with the us government and the white house 
judging from their statements they prefer euphemisms to 
president bush the economy is in a serious slowdown alan 
greenspan the federal reserve chairman prefers meaningful 
downturn 
michael boskin chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers had called the downturn a lull but in commenting 
late last week on the big jump in november unemployment he 
elaborated on his view to wit 
the decline in employment in november and the large revision 
in the job decline in october confirm that the economy is 
contracting noticeably in the fourth quarter 
in contrast independent assessors of economic activity have 
been using the r word for weeks or months openly blatantly 
boldly for obvious reasons preferring not to wait for the 
semiofficial definition 
the obviousness of their impatience is that the definition 
relied on by historians and the government two straight quarters 
of shrinking gross national product isnt available until about 
seven months into recession 
moreover what seems to be a growing number of economic analysts 
dont give a hoot for the formal decalaration 
says economist robert barbera of shearson lehman brothers for 
our part we continue to believe that the united states is in the 
fifth month of a recession that will extend into the middle of next 
year 
and albert sindlinger of sindlinger amp co whose staff 
telephones about 4000 households a month to inquire into their 
financial affairs finds most people believe the economy has been 
in recession all year long 
the question of recession yes or no was decided long ago at 
the national association of realtors which forecast that the 
economy will remain in a recession through much of 1991 with 
sustained growth resuming in 1992 
there are perhaps good reasons why government officials shy from 
the word one being that to declare a recession exists might 
exacerbate the situation another is that what the government says 
is not easily retracted 
but government has demonstrated in other economic areas a 
similar verbal dexterity in the avoidance of unpleasant terms 
the recent federal budget agreement for example was said to 
include a fiveyear 500 billion deficit reduction partly the 
result of spending cuts but many independent analysts claim they 
can find little sign of reduction 
believe me when the fat lady sings the 1991 deficit will be 
higher than it was in 1990 says james c miller cochairman of 
the tax foundation 
miller who learned a bit about deficits as president reagans 
budget director says the main reason is that spending will go up 
by at least 100 billion more than the entire federal government 
spent as late as 1961 
while a deficitreduction package that raises deficits might 
be seen as an astonishing miscommunication some commentators 
believe a recession that isnt called one until after its over is 
being less than forthright 
there is nothing sacred about the semiofficial definition of 
recession why for instance does it take two straight quarters of 
economic shrinkage isnt a year when there are two poor 
quarters though not consecutive just as painful asks 
investment adviser john dessauer 
meanwhile there is a chance the current downturn might already 
fit one of the broader definitions of recession offered by 
greenspan 
a recession he said is a process of deterioration in which 
events feed on each other to induce economy into a cumulative 
decline 
</TEXT>
