<TEXT>
 
editors note its viewed as a symbol of growing religious 
tolerance in the city of the popes an islamic house of worship 
virtually in the shadow of the vatican the architect of the 
mosque expected to be completed next year is a roman catholic who 
feels it is one of the most important monuments to be built in rome 
this century 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
an islamic mosque is rising in this seat of the 
roman catholic church something that would have been almost 
unthinkable a few decades ago 
not just any mosque its a 45 million complex capable of 
seating 2000 and believed to be the biggest islamic house of 
worship in all of europe 
and in a historic gesture of christianmoslem tolerance one of 
the first visitors to the mosque could be pope john paul ii 
we will invite him to our inauguration and i am almost 
positive he will come says abdul qayyum khan director of the 
islamic cultural center of italy 
the ceremony is tentatively set for the spring the vatican says 
it is too early to say whether john paul will attend but stresses 
that he is dedicated to pursuing dialogue with islam and other 
religions 
in any case the fact that a huge mosque has risen virtually in 
the back yard of the vatican is an unmistakable symbol of mutual 
tolerance between two faiths with ancient rivalries 
i think this mosque is one of the most important monuments 
built in rome in this century says paolo portoghesi a roman 
caholic who is the main architect of the mosque it is an 
expression of religious liberty and religious dialogue in the 
modern world 
yet delays in the project may have been linked to fears in some 
circles that the mosques minaret would be higher than the dome of 
st peters basilica located about 2 miles away across the tiber 
river 
there are deep hostilities in some parts of roman society for 
minorities portoghesi says there have been battles because 
naturally not everyone was in agreement on building a mosque in 
rome we had to overcome many obstacles 
the project is about threequarters finished still to be 
completed are the minaret a twostory cultural center and a 
landscaped public garden the complex will include a 500seat 
conference hall and one of the largest moslem libraries in the 
west with books in arabic english and italian 
we hope everything will be finished within six months before 
next summer says khan a pakistani who is overseeing the 
project we hope we will be able to use the mosque for our 
festival prayers after the ramadan 
with the arrival in recent years of thousands of immigrants from 
countries such as morocco tunisia and algeria islam has become 
increasingly visible in overwhelmingly roman catholic italy 
there are no official figures on the number of moslems in italy 
and khan is reluctant to make an estimate but italian media 
reports have put the number at more than 300000 nationwide 
including 50000 in rome 
we really needed a place where we could say our friday 
prayers says khan sitting in a temporary office in a trailer on 
the construction site we used to rent apartments or halls but 
they could accommodate 50 60 or at most 100 people the number was 
increasing all the time and we were shifting from place to place 
looking for more room 
because immigration is a new phenomenon and many of the new 
arrivals survive by taking jobs that most italians dont want the 
moslem community is still looking to assert itself in italian 
society 
one of the most prominent moslem names in italy is prince karim 
aga khan spiritual leader of the worlds 15 million ishmaili 
moslems although he lives in france the aga khan developed a 
jetset resort on the island of sardinia and is a familiar figure 
in italian social circles 
there are nearly 1000 christian churches in rome and two large 
and six small synagogues but unlike london paris and other major 
european capitals rome has never had a mosque 
the idea for a mosque in the city of popes goes back some 
decades but the project didnt start taking shape until the 
vatican announced in 1974 that pope paul vi had no objections the 
decision reflected the new openness to other religions set out in 
the 196265 second vatican council 
romes communistled city government of the time then donated an 
undeveloped 75acre plot at the foot of monte antenne in the 
exclusive parioli district 
there had been a kind of reluctance to have a mosque in the 
heart of the catholic world khan says a general argument was 
that the moslems do not permit a church in their own holiest places 
like mecca and medina but with the passing of time and the change 
of circumstances the project was deemed necessary 
still it took another decade before bulldozers went into 
action work was blocked because conservationists and local 
residents objected that construction would ruin the environment and 
cause traffic problems 
the final hurdles were cleared when the islamic cultural center 
pledged to plant 100 trees on the site and build a lighted access 
road routing traffic away from heavily populated areas 
when construction finally began in late 1984 officials 
predicted work would be completed in three years but various 
legal financial and bureaucratic problems slowed the project 
the cost was originally put at 30 million to be covered by 
contributions from moslem individuals and more than 20 moslem 
countries led by saudi arabia and iraq with 7 million apiece 
after the price tag soared to 45 million and the money nearly 
ran out saudi king fahd earlier this year personally donated the 
extra 15 million needed to complete the project khan says 
the latest delay involves the height of the minaret a slender 
circular tower attached to the mosque 
the minaret was designed to be 128 feet high but the islamic 
cultural center was recently told that a special license is 
required for any structure over 82 feet 
for the moment pending the goahead from regional officials 
the minaret remains wrapped in scaffolding and flanked by idle 
cranes 
khan insists the delay is strictly a matter of bureaucracy and 
has nothing to do with the rumors the minaret would be even taller 
than st peters in fact the dome of st peters is about four 
times higher than the planned minaret 
the minaret has also raised fears among neighborhood residents 
that its balcony would be used by a muezzin or crier to call the 
faithful to prayer five times a day 
but khan has promised them the tower wont be used for that 
traditional practice 
the inhabitants were a little afraid that we might be calling 
people to prayers at 430 or 5 in the morning khan says we 
told them no the minaret is just a symbolic thing without it 
the mosque is not really a mosque 
</TEXT>
