editors note second only to its steaks perhaps kansas city 
in the 1920s and 30s was known for its jazz and swinging nighclubs 
featuring the likes of count basie and charlie parker there are 
still plenty of jazz musicians in the city and several 
organizations are struggling to keep the tradition alive but few 
today can make a lic full time 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when little willving making musiie littlefield wrote the 
popular tune goin to kansas city in the early 1900s jazz 
musicians flocked here for the the good life and plenty of gigs 
nightclubs lined the streets and the joints were jumping from 
early evening to early morning seven days a week 
today hundreds of jazz musicians and a halfdozen jazz 
organizations are struggling to keep kansas citys jazz tradition 
alive about 400 jazz and blues soloists and more than 70 bands are 
competing for a shrinking share of the economic pie 
the money coming in from the city corporations and the public 
isnt enough to sustain a healthy jazz community in kansas city 
most musicians say 
the city has a certain amount of money and the jazzt to fame 
here in his hometown in the 30s count basie was a regular in the 
clubs here 
but with the end of pendergasts political career in 1938 after 
his indictment on tax evasion charges came the end of the jazz 
heyday 
reform elements took over nightclubs and cabarets were shut 
down jobs for musicians dried up and the kansas city bands took to 
the road 
oldtimers who remember the jazz scene as it used to be lament 
the way things are now 
jackson says finding a gig was easy back then but today not 
even 10 percent of the citys musicians can live by music alone 
i feel sad people as a whole do not support jazz in this 
town jackson says it is pathetic people like to listen but 
they dont want to spend money for it 
the city is not living up to the past reputation says kathe 
kaul head organizer of the annual kansas city jazz festival 
its a different time 
