katydids reprise katydids 
 
to some ears the next blip in the trendhappy rock world will 
be third generation poprock bands who owe allegiance to the 
beatles hollies and raspberries american bands such as seattles 
posies have deservedly received attention but dont neglect the 
katydids from britain 
the katydids selftitled debut is a sparkling collection of pop 
tunes energetically performed singer susie hug and guitarist adam 
seymour wrote all 11 songs 
lights out read my lips one of the few songs in recent 
years to prominently feature a tambourine is strong enough that 
you overlook the cliche 
the rockigg stop start and melancholy girl in a jigsaw 
puzzle both deal with the eternal subject of faltering 
relationships all above me and what will the angels say 
show a strong religious influence but as are many good pop songs 
they are vague enough to have multiple interpretations 
producer nick lowe no stranger to strong pop music has never 
been known to fiddle incessantly with an arrangement he believes 
in capturing the most inspired take and wrapping up recording 
an approach that serves the katydids well 
this band wont win any awards for originality heavy weather 
traffic owes an obvious debt to the who and dr rey could be 
matched with the beatles dr robert 
still this is a bright debut 
by david bauder associated press writer 
 
dear 23 david geffen co the posies 
 
like talking heads 77 and rems 1983 album murmur 
the posies majorlabel debut is a rock milestone an album that 
progressive bands six or seven years from now will cite as an 
influence 
the seattlebased quartet sets out to redefine the early 
psychedelic sound that blossomed in the mid to late60s and 
succeeds with thrilling harmonies and jangly guitars their chorus 
structure on golden blunders for example echoes the hollies 
i love jennifer eccles from 1968 
but the posies are not merely a throwback band their lyrics by 
singerguitarists jonathan auer and kenneth stringfellow exhibit 
refreshing levels of wit and depth 
the song title golden blunders is a play on the beatles 
golden slumbers the tunes sobering subject is the heavy 
consequences of unprotected sex pregnancy and early marriage 
men and women please beware dont pretend you care nothing 
lasts when theres nothing there the posies warn 
much of the material reflects the songwriters youth their main 
concerns are love doubt and separation but the posies prove that 
even these wellworn subjects can sparkle with some clever 
handling she left me alone claiming wed run out of things to 
talk about i was crushed of course but at least ive got something 
i can write about they sing on any other way 
it seems appropriate even inevitable that the posies hail from 
the pacific northwest where many 1960s flower children still 
nurture the dream of a new age the posies are a part of that 
future 
by david dishneau associated press writer 
