not long ago lawrence block wrote a mystery 
series chronicling the travails of one bernie rhodenbarr a burglar 
who constantly broke in somewhere only to stumble across a murder 
and implicate himself 
rhodenbarr of course had to solve the murders to protect his 
neck 
the tone was amusing 
not so blocks books about excop matthew scudder the mood in 
those including his eighth and newest one a ticket to the 
boneyard is decidedly different 
dark i suppose is the word block said in an interview 
the one that is coming out next year down on the killing 
floor is done and its also a very dark book 
much of the darkness in boneyard flows from the villain 
james leo motley a remorseless killer who relentlessly and 
cleverly hunts down his victims 
people have said he is the most fully realized villain that 
ive done block said hes not based on an acquaintance i 
have not met this chap and do not want to 
he wrote the first three matt scudder books in 1974 
he and i had points in common block said he lives in a 
hotel on west 57th street when the series began he was recently 
separated from his wife and children and recently retired from the 
new york police department and drinking a lot in a saloon on ninth 
avenue 
i was living on west 58th street recently separated from my 
wife and three daughters and spending a lot of my time in the very 
saloon that scudder hung out in 
in other ways our background and nature were very different 
ive married since then seven years ago scudder has not i quit 
drinking i quit before he did when i started writing the books it 
never occurred to me that either of us would ever stop 
block proudly recounts that policemen have told him they like 
the scudder series they say the way he acts and reacts and the 
way his mind works is very believable block briefly was an 
auxiliary policeman in new york 
scudder is interesting to write about because he evolves his 
creator says 
the books are as much about him as they are about the cases 
block said 
that was not true of classic private detective fiction 
raymond chandler wrote that a detective should be someone who 
exists as a window through which we see the world i think that was 
fine when chandler did it i wouldnt be interested in writing that 
kind of book 
he said he is pleased people often ask for more books on bernie 
rhodenbarr who last appeared in 1983s the burglar who painted 
like mondrian his favorite 
block said he thinks hes done with rhodenbarr but he also 
thought that about scudder after the sixth book in that series 
noting i dont have a lot of control over what i write next 
my typical writing pattern is that ill write a book in a 
month to six weeks and spend the rest of the year thinking about 
the next one the enjoyable time is the two to three weeks between 
having finished writing a book and starting to agonize over the 
next one he said 
he started writing and selling stories while at antioch college 
in ohio he dropped out for a year to work as an editor for a new 
york literary agency and continued to write back at antioch he 
said he couldnt focus on school work 
my interest was writing and i grudged the time i had to spend 
on assignments and classes he said the school suggested i 
might be happier elsewhere ive been writing ever since 
he was always able to make a living 
hollywood made the scudder novel eight million ways to die 
into a movie starring jeff bridges and changed the hero to a 
heroine to cast whoopi goldberg in burglar taken from the 
burglar in the closet one of blocks early books deadly 
honeymoon was filmed as nightmare honeymoon 
he also wrote seven books in the late 1960s and early 70s about 
evan tanner a freelance spy and one of those may become a movie 
he wrote four about chip harrison two are comic novels about a 
young mans coming of age i liked writing that voice so much i put 
him to work for a private detective and wrote two mysterie 
he also has written some books not in series but publishers and 
bookstores like series he said 
it makes it a little closer to brandname advertising theres 
a preexisting audience for each volume he said 
readers like the same only different i find that myself as a 
reader sometimes if a writer will come out with a new series book 
ill read it i want to spend time with those characters 
