the worst twomonth stretch of layoffs since 
the 198182 recession pushed civilian unemployment to a threeyear 
high of 59 percent in november the government said 
payrolls fell by 267000 last month the labor department said 
friday after a 180000job loss in october since june when the 
unemployment rate was 52 percent nearly 1 million americans have 
joined the ranks of the unemployed 
following the grim news the federal reserve and a handful of 
banks moved to cut interest rates 
 
washington ap growth in consumer credit slowed to a 
seasonally adjusted 147 billion in october the government 
reported analysts said it was another sign of a weakening economy 
the federal reserve on friday said consumer credit grew at an 
annual rate of 24 percent down from a revised 46 percent rate 
posted in september the september rate was even slower than the 
49 percent advance originally reported 
revolving or credit card debt increased 156 billion or an 
annual rate of 86 percent down from a 129 percent gain in 
september and a 133 percent advance a month earlier 
 
detroit ap more than 30000 auto workers nearly all of them 
at general motors corp plants will have next week off as the auto 
industry wrestles with a recession 
gm ford motor co and chrysler corp said friday they plan to 
shut down all or parts of a dozen assembly plants for the week of 
dec 10 keeping 32380 workers at home the closures stem from 
slow dealer orders 
gm also said it will lay off 50470 workers when it shuts down 
18 assembly factories in 14 states the week of dec 17 the last 
week before the industrys traditional shutdown between the 
christmas and new years holidays 
 
philadelphia ap a jury friday awarded 6 million to a state 
supreme court justice saying the philadelphia inquirer defamed him 
in a reprint of a 1983 series about the courts conduct 
the jury which deliberated nine hours over two days following a 
sevenweek trial found the reprint was false and defamatory but 
that the original series was not false 
the award was the second libel judgment against the inquirer 
this year william hangley the inquirers lawyer said the paper 
will appeal the verdict 
 
