<TEXT>
pratt amp whitney forges an alliance 
with germanys daimlerbenz to develop a new generation of 
highthrust jet engines 
general electric co sues claiming the deal violates its 
agreement with daimlerbenz then ge drops the suit and announces 
this fall it is exploring a joint venture with pratt amp whitney to 
develop a supersonic jet engine 
like countries forging alliances against a common foe 
jetengine makers are joining forces in everchanging combinations 
making it almost impossible to know which companies are rivals and 
which are partners 
joint ventures help enginemakers share astronomical development 
costs which results in superior engines by combining the 
technological strengths of various companies and even widen a 
companys customer base by giving it access to a rivals loyal 
customers industry experts say 
things are happening very fast said david vadas an 
economist with the aerospace industries association a 
washingtonbased lobbying group when you have the big boys 
pratt amp whitney ge and rollsroyce going into joint ventures 
there is no turning back 
development of a new jet engine costs between 1 billion to 2 
billion the development costs for the supersonic engine that ge 
and pratt amp whitney are contemplating could reach a staggering 45 
billion 
perhaps 80 percent of jet engines built over the next two 
decades will be produced by international partnerships said mark 
a bobbi an analyst with forecast international in newtown conn 
which follows the aerospace industry that eventually will increase 
to almost 100 percent he said 
the nature of new engines and new aircraft almost dictates it 
because of the costs and risks bobbi said 
sales of commercial engines could amount to between 100 billion 
and 150 billion during the next 15 years bobbi said 
jetengine makers form two basic kinds of alliances the most 
common is known as a risksharing partnership in which a number of 
companies contribute parts technology and financing for an engine 
that bears one companys name 
but several partners also may form an independent company that 
produces its own engines like east hartfordbased international 
aero engines created in 1983 by pratt amp whitney rollsroyce ltd 
of great britain and others 
ge pioneered the trend in 1971 by teaming with snecma a french 
rival to form cfm international cfm produces the highly 
successful cfm56 series for short to mediumrange twin engine 
planes like the boeing 737 
east hartfordbased pratt amp whitney launched its first civilian 
partnership in 1973 teaming with daimlerbenz and fiat aviazione 
of italy to build high thrust engines for widebody jets volvo 
flyg motor of sweden eventually joined the consortium which builds 
the pw2000 series for planes like the boeing 757 
by 1988 janes all the worlds aircraft an industry 
publication listed six major jet engine manufacturing alliances 
pratt amp whitney a division of united technologies corp is 
involved in seven major partnership programs ge is now working on 
at least five jointly produced engines 
an alliance between pratt amp whitney and ge would be the most 
surprising of all the two companies have been slugging it out 
since the 1970s for primacy in the jetengine market 
pratt amp whitney controlled 100 percent of the market until 1970 
but ge is now regarded as the biggest jetengine maker pratt amp 
witney logged 12 billion in orders and options last year vs 
ges 15 billion 
the companies announced in october they were exploring joint 
development of a supersonic jet engine to power planes faster and 
bigger than the frenchbritish concorde powered by an engine built 
by rollsroyce and snecma 
there was no way either company could do it alone from a 
technological or financial viewpoint said donald rudolph 
managing director for development and planning at pratt amp whitney 
everybody recognized it is so big that you need help 
the companies informed the us justice department of their 
plans but said they dont anticipate antitrust problems if the 
deal goes through they will be working together on the supersonic 
engine only and will compete in other areas generally antitrust 
issues dont arise because the partners are from different 
countries 
joint ventures can breed superior engines by combining the best 
technology of the various partners said craig hekking another 
analyst with forecast international 
take the v2500 engine built by international aero engines 
besides pratt amp whitney and rollsroyce iae partners include 
motoren und turbinen union daimlers aerospace division italys 
fiat aviazione and japanese aero engines corp 
the v2500 engine put into service in 1989 is built in modules 
with each partner responsible for a specific section the engines 
are then assembled at pratt amp whitney and rollsroyce plants 
rollsroyce builds the highpressure compressor pratt the 
combustor and highpressure turbine japanese aero engines corp 
contributes the lowpressure compressor system while motoren und 
turbinen union builds the lowpressure turbine fiat aviazione 
builds the gearbox 
enginemakers also dont seem very worried about rivals gaining 
access to their trade secrets 
ge raised the issue in its 12 billion lawsuit against pratt amp 
whitney which it dropped after daimlerbenz agreed to continue 
consulting with ge but on smaller engines but others say most 
enginemakers are roughly equal in terms of technology 
because engines like the v2500 are built in modules a company 
contributing one piece wouldnt know how the other modules are put 
together said nick tomassetti the former iae president who is now 
back at pratt amp whitney 
iae has received 75 billion worth of orders for the v2500 so 
far and expects orders to reach 20 billion by 2004 
</TEXT>
