<TEXT>
a third chinese city announced plans monday to 
open a securities exchange as interest in stock and bond markets 
rebounds from a period of official discouragement 
shanghai is scheduled to open chinas first fullfledged 
securities market on dec 19 and the shenzhen special economic 
zone plans to open one next year 
the newcomer is the zhuhai special economic zone located near 
shenzhen in southeastern chinas guangdong province the zones are 
areas that have more freedom than most cities to experiment in 
economic reforms 
zhuhai mayor liang guangda said a task force is preparing to 
open a securities market next year the official china daily 
reported the report indicated the market will focus on stocks 
unlike the upcoming shanghai market that will handle mainly 
government bonds 
the new markets will consolidate transactions currently handled 
by dozens of small unlinked counters in major cities 
liangs announcement reflects the new security market fever 
after more than a year of official coolness toward marketoriented 
reforms in general after crushing a popular democracy movement 
last year the conservative leaders who came to the fore denounced 
capitalist influences on society and the economy 
in recent months however authorities have begun viewing 
securities markets as a useful tool for raising muchneeded 
capital they are most interested in using the markets to sell 
state treasury bonds to help cover a growing budget deficit 
last week the government started up a nationwide computerized 
bonds trading system there has been heavy publicity in the 
official media about the new system and the coming shanghai market 
authorities are less enthusiastic about stocks because they 
transfer ownership of companies from state hands to the private 
sector the government allowed the first stock issue under 
communist rule in 1985 and a brief period of stock fever followed 
but most issues were made available only to employees of the 
companies involved and are not actively traded 
economists recently have revived interest in stocks by 
presenting them as a way of tapping private savings to aid 
industrial expansion and modernization 
the official china daily newspaper last week published an 
argument by a group of economists on behalf of stocks and markets 
the newspaper boldly likened the new interest in all kinds of 
securities to a prairie fire spreading across the country 
irresistable and irreversible 
</TEXT>
