veteran cotton ginner wc gunter stood 
in disbelief as he watched over millions of tiny white pillows 
being harvested in the rolling fields of this west texas farming 
town 
the crop wasnt supposed to be there this year gunter said 
mother nature gave us the greatest christmas gift we could ask 
for 
twentyone dry days of above 100 degrees in june had threatened 
most of the 32 million acres of cotton in the 25county region 
which produces a quarter of the nations cotton but sporadic 
rainfall in late july and early august helped the withering plants 
the latesummer moisture combined with a warm dry fall 
revived the crop into what is expected to be one of the strongest 
yields in the last decade 
crop observers are forecasting a total yield of 27 million 
bales in texas which is the nations biggest cotton producer 
thats up 69 percent over last years 16 million bales and 4 
percent above the us department of agricultures october estimate 
of 26 million 
