a federal judge on monday formally consolidated 
65000 asbestos injury claims against eaglepicher industries inc 
in a major step toward resolving a natiowide legal and medical 
crisis 
us district judge jack b weinstein certified a class action 
suit after a daylong hearing on a settlement proposal for 
eaglepicher that faces opposition from nearly all victims 
attorneys involved in the case 
attorneys said they would fight weinsteins consolidation of the 
cases saying the companys 625 million longterm settlement plan 
provides too little money and too few safeguards for victims of 
lung cancer and other respiratory ailments 
weinstein faces an additional roadblock in the formoof a 
petition filed monday in us bankruptcy court in cincinnati 
seeking to force eaglepicher involuntarily into bankruptcy 
proceedings under federal law the bankruptcy petition puts all 
other court action involving the company on hold 
but weinstein said the involuntary bankruptcy filing was 
fradulent on its face and he was moving ahead immediately to 
certify the class action in spite of the bankruptcy petition he 
also froze all litigation involving eaglepicher except to pay 45 
million in previously settled claims 
the cincinnatibased industrial products manufacturer has said 
it would have to seek bankruptcy court refuge if no solution to its 
asbestos problems were reached soon eaglepicher is liable for 
injuries caused by cement products containing asbestos it made from 
1931 to 1971 
the company has spent 540 million in the last five years on the 
issue and faces an estimated 600 million in future claims new 
claims against the company are being filed at an average of 20000 
annually 
eaglepicher chairman thomas petry said he was pleased weinstein 
moved to create the class action he called the involuntary 
bankruptcy petition a desperate attempt to circumvent and 
derail these proceedings 
the motion was filed by three asbestos victims who want 
eaglepicher placed under bankruptcy court supervision on grounds 
the company had failed to meet 19200 in settlement payments the 
company said it had met all obligations to the victims creditors 
lenders and other businesses 
plaintiffs lawyers acknowledged the filing was a strategic 
maneuver to try to block the settlement plan being considered by 
weinstein it would create a trust consisting of cash and company 
stock to compensate workers made sick inhlaing asbestos 
weinstein also appointed former federal judge marvin frankel to 
study whether eaglepicher claimants would receive more money in a 
bankruptcy or through the proposed settlement he also said he 
planned to hold hearings on the fairness of the plan in new york 
cincinnati and detroit 
lawyers complained the judge is forcing a national asbestos 
settlement without their endorsement weinstein wants a national 
plan to avoid long and costly trials that sap money for victims 
some of whom have died before being compensated 
currently more than 90000 asbestos cases clog state and 
federal courts a separate case involves the cashstrapped manville 
trust fund which faces 130000 claims and is being reorganized 
under orders from weinstein 
the plaintiffs have been deprived of an opportunity to be 
heard said ron motley a charleston sc lawyer representing 
several thousand asbestos victims 
we are resigned to the impossibility of getting a fair hearing 
in this court said steven kazan an attorney for the asbestos 
victims of america which has about 18000 members 
only one of three lawyers appointed by weinstein to represent 
current eaglepicher victims has approved the plan and he does not 
have any asbestos clients more than 90 attorneys with 40000 
asbestos clients signed a petition monday opposing the settlement 
plan 
there is a massive lack of confidence in the settlement 
grant hering a new york plaintiffs lawyer told the judge for 
people who are victims who have suffered what they have suffered 
it is a gimmick they cant comprehend 
under the plan eaglepicher would pay 460 million in annual 
payments over 20 years into the trust plus 120 million from the 
companys cash flow it also would contribute 45 million to pay 
settlements already negotiated 
the trust would receive 25 percent of eaglepicher stock and 50 
percent if the company failed to meet its annual payments after 
five years 
in an apparent attempt to quell some of the criticism of the 
plan which was presented to the court last week weinstein 
modified it to grant the trust voting control of eaglepicher if 
the company failed to meet annual payments during the plans first 
five years 
he also said payments should begin by nov 30 1993 regardless 
of delays due to possible court appeals and that victims should 
not lose any rights agreed to in a settlement if eaglepicher 
declared bankruptcy 
</TEXT>
